<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ ACTIVITY 1 — INSTRUCTIONS -->
<div class="section" id="a1i">
  <div class="act-header">
    <div class="act-num"><div class="act-num-pip">1</div>Activity 1 of 6 · Setup</div>
    <h2 class="act-title">The Rule Switch Game</h2>
    <p class="act-desc">Measures whether old habits fire automatically when rules change — or whether your child pauses to understand the new rule before acting. This is the single most diagnostic activity in the assessment.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="setup-box">
    <h3>You will need</h3>
    <div class="setup-items">
      <div class="setup-item"><div class="setup-num">1</div><div class="setup-text"><strong>5 playing cards or paper cards</strong> — write one of these on each: 3, 7, 12, 25, 8</div></div>
      <div class="setup-item"><div class="setup-num">2</div><div class="setup-text">A flat surface with two sides — designate left and right</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>Phase 1 — Establish the rule (2 min)</h3>
    <p>Say to your child:</p>
    <div class="script">"We're going to sort these numbers. Odd numbers go left, even numbers go right. Go as fast as you can."</div>
    <p>Let them sort all five. Shuffle and repeat twice more. This builds the habit — it is not yet diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>Phase 2 — Switch the rule (the diagnostic moment)</h3>
    <p>Immediately after the third sort, without any pause, say:</p>
    <div class="script">"Good. New rule. Numbers less than 10 go left, numbers 10 or more go right."</div>
    <p>Present the cards again immediately. <strong>Watch closely. Do not react.</strong> You want to catch whether the old "odd/even" categorisation fires before the new one.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>Phase 3 — Introduce an ambiguous case</h3>
    <p>Add a new card: <strong>10</strong>. Announce:</p>
    <div class="script">"New rule: numbers you can get to by counting in 3s go left. Everything else goes right."</div>
    <p>Present all six cards. The number 12 is unambiguous (yes). The number 9 would be ambiguous — but the card you're watching is whether they pause on any card to mentally test it, or place everything immediately by feel.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="note-box"><strong>Note:</strong> A confident wrong placement is more diagnostic than a correct placement reached by checking. You are observing process, not outcome.</div>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <button class="btn-primary" onclick="goTo('a1o')">I've completed this activity →</button>
  </div>
</div>

