    <h2 class="act-title">The Story Maths Game</h2>
    <p class="act-desc">Measures whether your child constructs the meaning of a problem before solving, or matches surface language to a known operation. Read each story slowly. After the last word, say nothing and wait — you want their first-fire response, before self-correction.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="note-box"><strong>Key instruction:</strong> Tell your child to answer as soon as they know — don't wait to explain first. Read each story slowly and naturally, then say nothing. Observe the very first answer given.</div>
  <div class="story-cards">
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 1 · Baseline</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 7</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"Mia has 4 apples. She picks 3 more. How many apples does she have?"</div><div class="story-watch">Both types answer quickly. Slowness here signals anxiety rather than a cognitive signal.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 2 · Language swap</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 3</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"There are 7 birds on a wire. Some fly away. Now there are 4. How many flew away?"</div><div class="story-watch">"Flew away" replaces "minus." Children who surface-match will hesitate — the word doesn't say subtract.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 3 · Distractor detail</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 3</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"Tom has 6 sweets. He gives 2 to his sister and 1 to his dog. How many does he have left?"</div><div class="story-watch">The dog is the distractor. Does your child filter irrelevant emotional content, or does it affect their processing?</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 4 · Structural reversal ★ Highest signal</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 4</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"A bag had some oranges. I put in 5 more. Now there are 9. How many were in the bag before?"</div><div class="story-watch">Children who pattern-match "put in 5 more" will answer 14. Children who construct the story will subtract. This is the most diagnostic question.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 5 · Two steps</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 11</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"There are 12 children in a class. 4 go home sick. Then 3 new children arrive. How many children are in the class now?"</div><div class="story-watch">Requires two operations. Watch whether your child processes both steps or stops after the first.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 6 · Hidden comparison</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 16</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"Callum saved up £24. He spent some on a book. Now he has £8 less than he started with. How much does he have now?"</div><div class="story-watch">"£8 less than he started with" is a comparison, not a direct subtraction. Children must hold the original value and subtract 8 from it — not from the current stated amount.</div></div></div>
  </div>
