<div class="section" id="a3i">
  <div class="act-header">
    <div class="act-num"><div class="act-num-pip">3</div>Activity 3 of 6 · Setup</div>
    <h2 class="act-title">The Repetition and Pattern Game</h2>
    <p class="act-desc">Two parts. First: how your child handles extended repetition — and whether a format shift re-engages them. Second: what complexity of rule they construct when given complete freedom.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>Part A — 20 Flashcards (5 min)</h3>
    <p>Prepare 20 simple flashcards with addition and subtraction facts your child already knows confidently (e.g. 3+4, 8−3, 5+6, 7+7). Show them one by one at a steady pace. Your child calls out the answer as fast as possible. <strong>Keep a completely neutral face throughout.</strong> No feedback whatsoever.</p>
    <p>After card 20, immediately switch format — say the next three questions as word stories rather than showing a card. Watch whether engagement and energy visibly return.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>Part B — Make a Pattern (5 min)</h3>
    <p>Give your child paper and a pencil. Say:</p>
    <div class="script">"Now you make up a pattern — numbers, shapes, colours, anything at all — with a secret rule. Don't tell me the rule. I'll try to guess it."</div>
    <p>Give them up to 3 minutes. Say nothing. If they ask "what kind of pattern?" say only: <em>"Any kind you like."</em></p>
  </div>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <button class="btn-primary" onclick="goTo('a3o')">I've completed this activity →</button>
